Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio  
• From the balance sheet, total liabilities are the sum of Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable.  
  Accounts Payable = 302,000.00  
  Taxes Payable = 197,821.72  
  Total Liabilities = 302,000.00 + 197,821.72 = 499,821.72  
• Total Owner’s Equity = 14,390,936.99  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Owner’s Equity  
  = 499,821.72 / 14,390,936.99 ≈ 0.0347  
Rounded to two decimals, the ratio is about 0.03.

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin  
• From the income statement:  
  Net Profit = 1,390,936.99  
  Total Revenue = 3,956,433.90  
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (1,390,936.99 / 3,956,433.90) × 100 ≈ 35.17%  

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
• From the cash flow statement:  
  Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -1,182,491.05  
• Total Current Liabilities (from the balance sheet) = 499,821.72  
• Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Total Current Liabilities  
  = -1,182,491.05 / 499,821.72 ≈ -2.3649  
Rounded to two decimals, the ratio is about -2.36.

Thus, the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.03",
    "Net Profit Margin": "35.17%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-2.36"
  }
}
